XPS spectra of the samples are presented in Fig. 3
                        . The peaks belonging to Zn 2p1/2 (1044.9 eV) and Zn 2p3/2 (1021.9 eV) in Fig. 3a, the peaks referring to In 3d3/2 (452.5 eV) and In 3d5/2 (444.9 eV) in Fig. 3b as well as peaks of S 2p1/2 (162.8 eV) and S 2p3/2 (161.5 eV) of ZIS in Fig. 3c are respectively consistent with Zn2+, In3+ and S2− chemical states [33], which proofs the successful preparation of ZIS. Compared with parent ZIS, the Zn 2p peaks of Ni3P/ZIS and CDs/Ni3P/ZIS slightly shift toward higher binding energy (Fig. 3a), indicating that strong interaction exists between the Ni3P or CDs/Ni3P and ZIS. The In 3 d and S 2p XPS spectra show good correspondence among the peaks of ZIS, Ni3P/ZIS and CDs/Ni3P/ZIS (Fig. 3b & c), demonstrating the electronic configurations of In 3 d and S 2p orbitals are retained. Ni 2p spectra of the samples in Fig. 3d all possess three peaks. The peaks at 861.2 and 852.0 eV are respectively consistent with the satellite peak and the characteristic peak of Ni0, which is derived from Ni–Ni bond in Ni3P and metallic Ni [34]. The presence of Ni2+ peak at 855.6 eV relating to Ni–O bond indicates the partial surface oxidation in Ni3P [35]. Noteworthily, these peaks of Ni3P/ZIS and CDs/Ni3P/ZIS significantly shift to higher binding energy in comparison with those of Ni3P, which again demonstrates the strong interaction between Ni3P and ZIS [36]. The increased proportion of Ni0 in CDs/Ni3P/ZIS further suggests the partial reduction of Ni3P to monomeric Ni during the preparation of CDs/Ni3P/ZIS under N2 atmosphere (Table 1
                        ), which is in line with XRD results. The peak at 132.8 eV corresponding to P–O bond and the double peaks of P 2p3/2 (128.8 eV) and P 2p1/2 (129.6 eV) assigning to P–Ni bonds in P 2p spectrum revalidate the presence of Ni3P phase (Fig. 3e) [35]. By comparing, the P 2p peaks in CDs/Ni3P/ZIS all shift to higher binding energies, which reflects the lower electron cloud density around P in CDs/Ni3P/ZIS and that the P sites function as electron donors [37]. The peaks at 284.8, 286.4 and 288.8 eV in C 1s spectrum of CDs/Ni3P/ZIS (Fig. 3f) are respectively ascribed to the sp2 hybridized carbon (C–C), epoxidized hydroxyl carbon (C–O) and carboxylated carbon bond (OC–O), which demonstrates the successful introduction of CDs [38]. These oxygen-containing groups may improve the water solubility of the photocatalysts.
